==Old English==
===Etymology===
West Germanic ''*harƀista-'', from Indo-European ''*kerp-, *skerp-''.  Cognate with Old Frisian [[herfst]], Old Saxon [[herƀist]] (Dutch [[herfst]]), Old High German [[herbist]] (German [[Herbst]]).  The IE root is also the source of Greek [[καρπος]] ‘fruit’, Latin [[carpere]] ‘pick, pluck’, Middle Irish [[corrán]] ‘sickle’, Lithuanian [[kirpti]] ‘cut’, Old Church Slavonic [[чрьпати]] (Russian [[черп]] ‘sickle’).

A North Germanic variant ''*harƀusta-'' was the source of Old Norse [[haust]] (Swedish [[höst]]).

